  "text": "The dynamic analysis with the Dortmunder model demonstrated the significance of velocity and acceleration. [CITATION_1] The task of raising objects of various weights (no load, 20, and 40 kg) from floor to elbow height was simulated in three conditions: ''slow,'' in which the lift was completed in 2 sec; ''medium,'' in which the lift was completed in 1.5 sec; and ''fast,'' in which the lift was completed in 1 sec. In the slow condition, compressive forces at the L5/S1 were similar to static conditions. At medium speed, peak compressive forces were about 20% higher than under static conditions. At high speed, peak compressive forces were roughly 50% higher than under static conditions. Jager et al. [CITATION_2] also simulated a jerking motion, assuming that all of the upward acceleration was completed in 0.1 sec. Under these conditions, the peak L5/S1 compression for lifting a 20-kg load from the floor was approximately 8000 N, more than double the peak load in static conditions and considerably higher than compressive loads shown to cause mechanical damage in cadaver tissues. Shear forces were not reported for the dynamic analyses.",
